Metaphysics refers to the study of questions that cannot be answered directly by perception through rational reasoning and logic. Metaphysics is the basic principle of philosophy, which aims to explain the basic nature of existence and the world. The Chinese translation of "metaphysics" is derived from the phrase "the metaphysical is called the Tao, and the physical is called the instrument" in the Book of Changes(Meiji period) translated from metaphysical. The branch of metaphysics that includes ontology, natural theology, and the extended problem. Ontology is the "study of which terms represent real entities and which merely represent concepts." Metaphysical naturalism, the denial of the existence of God, is based on the theory that all phenomena can be explained by the concept of natural causes.Philosophy of mind is the branch of philosophy that deals with the nature of consciousness and its relationship to bodies (especially the brain). Dualism and monism are the two main schools of thought that discuss the relationship between mind and body. Epistemology is a branch of philosophy that explores the nature, origin and scope of knowledge. ethics is a discipline that systematically ponders and studies human moral life;In this context, morality is defined as all the rules of conduct accepted by a group of people or a culture(the abstract study of the nature of ethical theory or criticism), normative ethics(It evaluates different moral values and suggests moral principles for right or wrong behavior. It studies what kind of moral behavior people should follow), applied ethics(the application of ethical theory to real life situations, including bioethics, political ethics, etc.), descriptive ethics(It gathers information about how people live, and summarizes it from observed patterns. It examines ethics not from preconceived theories, but from the real choices made and observed by actual moral agents, and from all the moral factors that contribute to those choices. It examines the ethics held by social groups.) The history of ethics includes Greece ethics and medieval Christian ethics. Part I:The ethical thought of humanism is represented by Walla and Montaigne.The ethics of the Reformation, represented by Calvin.Political ethics, represented by Machiavelli and others, modern ethics (17th-18th century, United Kingdom empirical ethics, representative figures:Hume et al., 17th-18th century, Continental rationalist ethics, representative figures:Spinoza et al., 18th century, France Enlightenment ethics, representative figures:Voltaire et al., 18th-19th century, Germany academic ethics, representative:Kant and Hegel, 18th-19th century, United Kingdom utilitarian ethics, representative figures:Bentham and Sidgwick, 19th century, United Kingdom evolutionary ethics, representative figures:Spencer and Huxley, et al., Late 19th Century, Germany Neo-Kantian Ethics, Representative:Li Kaier et al., Late 19th Century, Neo-Hegelian Ethics, Representative:Thomas Hill Green, etc.), transitional ethics (irrationalist ethics, representative figures:Kierkegaard, Schopenhauer, Nietzsche, etc.) Logic is the study of "the principles and criteria of valid inference and proof". Logic usually consists of three parts: inductive reasoning, abductive reasoning and deductive reasoning. It can be divided into formal logic and informal logic. Aesthetics is the study of the nature and meaning of beauty.
